<ns3273:section xmlns:ns3273="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.technologies.java.j2ee.introduction.j2eeApis.servletsJsps">

  <ns3274:title xmlns:ns3274="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Java on the Web Server (Servlets, JSP, Filters)</ns3274:title>
   <ns3275:para xmlns:ns3275="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
     Java EE defines a presentation layer logic container (often called the <ns3276:emphasis xmlns:ns3276="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">web container</ns3276:emphasis>) which can host deployable
     presentation layer components such as Servlets or Java Server Pages (JSP).
   </ns3275:para>
   <ns3277:para xmlns:ns3277="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
     Java Server Pages provide a convenient approach for generating the views of a 
     Model-View-Controller based architecture, and a means through which developers 
     <ns3278:emphasis xmlns:ns3278="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">without</ns3278:emphasis> Java skills can develop the XHTML (or any other
     markup language, such as SVG, WML or your own XML) front-end.
   </ns3277:para>
  <ns3279:para xmlns:ns3279="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Servlets form the backbone of most presentation layer applications, and often
    play the role of <ns3280:emphasis xmlns:ns3280="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">use-case controllers</ns3280:emphasis> in a model-view-controller
    scenario. They typically interface with Enterprise Java Beans (which provide the business data and logic, i.e.
    the model).
  </ns3279:para>
   <ns3281:para xmlns:ns3281="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
     Servlet containers like <ns3282:emphasis xmlns:ns3282="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Jakarta Tomcat</ns3282:emphasis> manage thread pools, 
     user sessions and networking for the presentation layer components, freeing the developer to 
     focus only on the business logic and functionality.
   </ns3281:para>
</ns3273:section>